								<div class="content">I&#39;m still totally unsold on the idea of carrying around a mobile medical station. I&#39;m not a professional athlete; I don&#39;t need real-time statistics on what every organ in my body is doing, how much energy I&#39;m using, etc.<br/>
<br/>
The Tarahumara people (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarahumara_people) can run 200 mile-stretches over a couple of days, and AFAIK they don&#39;t use fitbits, Nike smart watches, iWatches or anything else. They drink beer and eat beans and squirrels.<br/>
<br/>
Not just their young people, either - even the middle-aged and elderly can run enormous distances.<br/>
<br/>
Point is: teching yourself up doesn&#39;t make you healthier or fitter. Some of the most primitive people on the planet could put our best olympic athletes to shame.<br/>
<br/>
That said, of course, I said I&#39;m not sold on the idea. Maybe Apple will convince me, but if this really is a &#34;health&#34; statistics device, then no thanks.</div>
